---
export const prerender = true;
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Cups to mL: Essential Baking Measurement Guide" description="Convert cups to millilitres for baking with our comprehensive guide. Includes US vs metric cups, common ingredients, and measurement tips for perfect results." keywords="cups to ml, baking conversion, cup measurement, ml to cups, baking measurements, cooking cups, volume conversion baking">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Cooking</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">Cups to mL: Essential Baking Measurement Guide</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 27, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>American recipes use cups. European and Australian recipes use millilitres and grams. If you bake from international cookbooks or online recipes, you need to know how to convert between these systems accurately.</p>

      <h2>The Key Conversion</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">1 US cup = 236.59 mL (commonly rounded to 240 mL)</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">1 metric cup (AU/NZ) = 250 mL | 1 UK cup = 284 mL (rarely used)</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Common Cup Fractions Converted</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>1/4 cup = 59 mL</li>
        <li>1/3 cup = 79 mL</li>
        <li>1/2 cup = 118 mL</li>
        <li>2/3 cup = 158 mL</li>
        <li>3/4 cup = 177 mL</li>
        <li>1 cup = 237 mL</li>
        <li>1.5 cups = 355 mL</li>
        <li>2 cups = 473 mL</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Other Volume Measurements</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>1 tablespoon (US) = 14.8 mL (often rounded to 15 mL)</li>
        <li>1 teaspoon = 4.9 mL (often rounded to 5 mL)</li>
        <li>1 fluid ounce = 29.6 mL (often rounded to 30 mL)</li>
        <li>1 cup = 16 tablespoons = 8 fluid ounces</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why Cups Are Problematic for Baking</h2>
      <p>The cup system has a fundamental flaw: it measures volume, not weight. This matters because:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Flour varies enormously:</strong> 1 cup of sifted flour weighs about 120 g, but 1 cup scooped directly from the bag can weigh 150 g+</li>
        <li><strong>Brown sugar vs white sugar:</strong> Same cup, different weights (packed vs loose)</li>
        <li><strong>Liquid vs dry:</strong> Measuring techniques differ (liquid at eye level, dry levelled off)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>For consistent baking results, many professionals recommend converting cup recipes to grams using a scale.</p>

      <h2>Tips for Accurate Cup Measurements</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Flour:</strong> Spoon into the cup and level off with a knife — never scoop from the bag</li>
        <li><strong>Sugar:</strong> Scoop and level (unless the recipe says "packed")</li>
        <li><strong>Liquids:</strong> Use a clear measuring jug and read at eye level from the bottom of the meniscus</li>
        <li><strong>Butter:</strong> Use the wrapper markings (each stick has tablespoon lines) or weigh it</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/cooking" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Cooking Converter →</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
